<pretext>
    <article xml:id="notes">
        <worksheet margin="1in" bottom="1.25cm" xml:id="sec-II-1-sols">
        <title><m>\S II.1</m>: Connecting Elements</title>
            <page>
                <exercise workspace=".25in">
                    <title>Motivation: Relations </title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                        
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            Now that we know a lot about sets and set notation, we can talk about how sets can 
                        interact in meaningful ways. A fundamental interaction is called a <term>relation</term>.
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                
                </exercise>

                <exercise workspace=".5in">
                    <title>Definition and Example: Relation</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            A <term>relation</term> between sets <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> is
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            is a subset <m>R \subset A \times B</m>. We often indicate elements <m>(a,b) \in R</m>
                            by <m>a \sim_R b</m> or <m>aRb</m>.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Consider the sets <m>\N</m> and <m>P</m> of prime numbers. We'll define a relation <m>R</m>
                            on <m>\N \times P</m> by saying <m>aRb</m> if <m>b</m> divides <m>a</m>. Then we can note that
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>4R2</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>4 \not R 3</m> (<m>3</m> does not divide <m>4</m>)
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>2 \not R 4 </m> (<m>4</m> does not divide <m>2</m>)
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>12 \not R 6</m> (<m>(12,6) \not \in \N \times P</m>)
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                </exercise>

                <exercise workspace=".5in">
                    <title>Familiar Relations</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            The following are all relations on <m>\R \times \R</m>. Write at least three elements in each
                            relation as elements of <m>\R \times \R</m>.
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\lt</m>. Examples are <m>(1,2), (\pi,4), (\sqrt{2}, 2)</m>.
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\leq</m>. Examples are <m>(3,3), (0,2), (-4, -1)</m>.
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>=</m>. Examples are <m>(3,3), (1.8,1.8), (-1,-1) </m>.
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                    
                </exercise>
            </page>

            <page>
                <exercise workspace="5in">
                    <title>Representations of Relations</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            We can represent relations in multiple ways. Let <m>A= \{1, 2, 3, 4\}</m>, and 
                            <m>R \subset A \times A</m> be the relation defined by "<m>\lt</m>".
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            We can represent <m>A</m> as 
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        a subset of <m>A \times A</m>.
                                        <me>
                                            R= \{(1,2), (1,3), (1,4), (2,3), (2,4), (3,4) \}
                                        </me>
                                        
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        a table. We can represent <m>(a,b) \in A \times A</m> as
                                        <tabular>
                                            <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
                                                <cell><m>a</m></cell>
                                                <cell><m>b</m></cell>
                                            </row>
                                            <row>
                                                <cell><m>1</m></cell>
                                                <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                                            </row>
                                            <row>
                                                <cell><m>1</m></cell>
                                                <cell><m>3</m></cell>
                                            </row>
                                            <row>
                                                <cell><m>1</m></cell>
                                                <cell><m>4</m></cell>
                                            </row>
                                            <row>
                                                <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                                                <cell><m>3</m></cell>
                                            </row>
                                            <row>
                                                <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                                                <cell><m>4</m></cell>
                                            </row>
                                            <row>
                                                <cell><m>3</m></cell>
                                                <cell><m>4</m></cell>
                                            </row>
                                        </tabular>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        directed graphs. You can see directed graphs being used in a similar example
                                        in <url href="https://htmlpreview.github.io/?https://github.com/hulpke/csbook/blob/main/mathforcs.html#Ch2.S1">Figure 1 of section II.1</url>. 
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            If our relation is on <m>\R \times \R</m>, there is another familiar representation as a 
                            graph in the coordinate plane.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            For example, the relation <m>R_1 = \{(x,y) \in \R \times \R | (x,y) =( x, x^2)\}</m> is just the equation <m>y=x^2</m>.
                            We can view this relation as the <url href="https://www.desmos.com/calculator/zkizevnckc">graph of <m>y=x^2</m></url>.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            A similar example is the relation <m>R_2 = \{(x,y) \in \R \times \R | x^2 + y^2 = 1\}</m>. This relation is viewed 
                            as the <url href="https://www.desmos.com/calculator/hlnwsojjwq">graph of a circle of radius one</url>.
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                </exercise>
            </page>
            <page>
                <exercise workspace="3in">
                    <title>Definitions: Source, target, domain, and range</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            
                        </p>
                        
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            Let <m>R \subset A \times B</m> be a relation.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            The set <m>A</m> is called the <term>source</term> of <m>R</m>, and the 
                            set <m>B</m> is called the <term>target</term> of <m>R</m>.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            The set
                            <me>
                                D = \{a \in A | \exists b \in B, (a,b) \in R\}
                            </me>
                            is the <term>domain</term> of <m>R</m>.
                            
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            The set 
                            <me>
                                G = \{ b \in B | \exists a \in A, (a,b) \in R\}
                            </me>
                            is the <term>range</term> of <m>R</m>.
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                    
                </exercise>
                <exercise workspace="3in">
                    <title>Practice: Domain and Range</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            Let <m>S=\{1,2,3,4,5\}</m>, and <m>R \subset S \times S</m> be the relation 
                            <m>\{(a,b) \in S \times S | b \lt a\}</m>. What is the domain? What is the range?
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            The domain of <m>R</m> is <m>\{2,3,4,5\}</m>, while the range of <m>R</m> is
                            <m>\{1,2,3,4\}</m>.
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                </exercise>
            </page>

            
